{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772048135,"nonce":"Z/AAFFuEY/WUeng4gjTfuE5rlN0=","message":"[GitHub comment by i-m-mll on 2024-02-29T01:55:46Z]\n\nWhen training a point mass model on simple reaches, two `(f32[2],f32[2])` leaves (in `mu` and `nu`) corresponding to `Channel.input_proto` became `(None, None)` after passing through `train_step` once. This was the only change.\n\nThis is because those leaves are not trained (i.e. no gradients calculated) however they were included in the PyTree that was initially passed to `optimizer.init`. It happens that these are the only array parameters in the model PyTree that were not trainable in this case, but presumably the number of leaves that would change to `None` in `opt_state` across the first iteration would be even larger for a model with more array parameters (e.g. a muscle model).\n\nI've solved this by filtering the model by both the training filter spec *and* by `eqx.is_array`, before passing to `optimizer.init`:\n\n```python\nmodel_trainables = eqx.filter(eqx.filter(model, filter_spec), eqx.is_array)\nopt_state = self.optimizer.init(model_trainables)\n```\n\nPreviously, the model was only filtered by `eqx.is_array`.\n\nFiltering by `eqx.is_array` is still necessary because otherwise the filtered model might include (say) lambdas, for example if the `filter_spec` is a prefix. Then `optimizer` would raise an exception.","files":null}]}